<div class="container">
    <h1>💾 Understanding Databases in .NET</h1>

    <p>
        Databases are where your application stores and retrieves data.  
        In .NET, we commonly use <strong>SQL Server</strong> or <strong>SQLite</strong> with 
        <strong>Entity Framework Core</strong> to interact with the database.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>🔹 What is a Database?</h2>
    <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>
                A <strong>database</strong> is a structured collection of data that your application can read from and write to.  
                It organizes information in <strong>tables</strong> which contain rows (records) and columns (fields).
            </p>
            <p>
                Example: A <strong>Users</strong> table might have columns like <code>Id</code>, <code>Name</code>, <code>Email</code>.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>🔹 How .NET Works With Databases</h2>
    <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>
                In .NET, we usually use <strong>Entity Framework Core (EF Core)</strong> to interact with databases.  
                EF Core allows you to work with data as <strong>C# objects</strong> instead of writing SQL manually.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Define <strong>Models</strong> which represent your tables.</li>
                <li>Use a <strong>DbContext</strong> class to manage connections and queries.</li>
                <li>Perform operations like <strong>Create, Read, Update, Delete (CRUD)</strong> on your data.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>🔹 Example: User Model and DbContext</h2>
    <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>Here’s a simple example of a User model and DbContext:</p>
            <pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class User
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public string Email { get; set; }
}

public class AppDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet&lt;User&gt; Users { get; set; }

    protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder)
    {
        optionsBuilder.UseSqlServer("YourConnectionStringHere");
    }
}
            </code></pre>
            <p>
                ✅ This allows you to access the <strong>Users</strong> table via C# code and perform CRUD operations.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>🔹 Key Points About Databases in .NET</h2>
    <ul class="list-group mb-3">
        <li>Use <strong>EF Core</strong> for easier data access.</li>
        <li>Models represent <strong>tables</strong> in the database.</li>
        <li>DbContext manages <strong>connections and queries</strong>.</li>
        <li>CRUD operations let you <strong>create, read, update, and delete data</strong> from the database.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr />
    <p class="text-center text-muted">
        ✅ In short: Databases store your data, Models represent the data in C#, and DbContext helps your application interact with it easily.
    </p>

